{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514125","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514125"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:19:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:19:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12280"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12280"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.55,0.08,0.16,0.06,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4802"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96634"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4802","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4802"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12280"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79268"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"319"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"3579"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7705"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7758"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33135"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42729"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43995"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96634","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96634"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a six-hour history of severe pain, redness and watering in his right eye. He reports seeing halos around lights and his vision is significantly reduced. He feels nauseated and has vomited once before presentation. He has experienced similar symptoms twice in the past which resolved spontaneously. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 150/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His right eye shows conjunctival injection, a mid-dilated pupil that is poorly reactive to light, and a hazy cornea. The anterior chamber appears shallow. Intraocular pressure is 68 mmHg (10-21) in the right eye and 14 mmHg in the left eye. The acute condition is brought under control with medical therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate definitive management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Laser peripheral iridotomy","Surgical peripheral iridectomy","Trabeculectomy","Selective laser trabeculoplasty","Topical prostaglandin analogues"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of acute angle-closure glaucoma (AACG), including severe eye pain, redness, blurred vision, halos around lights, nausea, and vomiting. The markedly elevated intraocular pressure (68 mmHg), mid-dilated pupil, and shallow anterior chamber confirm the diagnosis. The history of previous similar episodes that resolved spontaneously suggests he has had subacute attacks in the past.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaser peripheral iridotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the definitive management for AACG after the acute attack has been controlled with medications. This procedure creates a small hole in the peripheral iris, allowing aqueous humor to flow directly from the posterior chamber to the anterior chamber, bypassing the pupillary block. This equalises pressure between the two chambers and widens the angle. It is typically performed in both eyes, as the fellow eye has a high risk of developing AACG if untreated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical peripheral iridectomy\u003C/strong\u003E involves surgically removing a small piece of peripheral iris to create a pathway for aqueous flow. While this achieves the same goal as laser iridotomy, it is more invasive and carries greater risks. It is generally reserved for cases where laser treatment is not possible (e.g., due to corneal opacity or lack of laser equipment).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrabeculectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is a filtering surgery that creates an alternative pathway for aqueous humor to exit the eye by forming a bleb under the conjunctiva. While effective at lowering intraocular pressure, it is not the first-line treatment for AACG. It is typically reserved for cases of chronic glaucoma that are unresponsive to medical therapy or when angle damage has occurred after AACG.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelective laser trabeculoplasty\u003C/strong\u003E uses laser energy to improve aqueous outflow through the trabecular meshwork. It is primarily used for open-angle glaucoma and is not effective in angle-closure glaucoma where the problem is access to the trabecular meshwork rather than trabecular function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical prostaglandin analogues\u003C/strong\u003E lower intraocular pressure by increasing uveoscleral outflow of aqueous humor. While they are first-line medications for chronic open-angle glaucoma, they are not the definitive treatment for AACG. They may be used as part of the ongoing management after iridotomy if there is residual pressure elevation due to chronic angle damage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute angle-closure glaucoma presents with severe eye pain, redness, blurred vision, halos around lights, and often nausea and vomiting.","Previous episodes of angle closure that resolved spontaneously (subacute attacks) are a risk factor for developing acute angle-closure glaucoma.","Laser peripheral iridotomy is the definitive management for acute angle-closure glaucoma after the acute attack has been controlled."],"references":["Pohl H, Tarnutzer AA. Acute Angle-Closure Glaucoma. N Engl J Med. 2018 Mar 08;378(10):e14. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMicm1712742","Schwenn O, Sell F, Pfeiffer N, Grehn F. Prophylactic Nd: YAG-laser iridotomy versus surgical iridectomy: a randomized, prospective study. Ger J Ophthalmol. 1995; 4:374\u2013379. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8751104/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79268"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12280"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79268","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79268"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T14:45:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T14:45:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4802"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96634"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"